  "opinion": "As a retired individual with a master’s degree and a deep curiosity about human behavior, I’ve observed how stereotypes can subtly shape experiences across generations. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theoretical concept—it’s a lived reality for many who face assumptions about their abilities based on gender, ethnicity, or background. For instance, when a young woman in my community, raised in a small Italian town like Lecce, feels she must prove her math skills to counter the idea that ‘girls aren’t good at science,’ her performance may suffer not because of innate ability but because of the mental load of self-doubt. This phenomenon isn’t limited to any one group; it affects people of all backgrounds who internalize societal expectations. I’ve seen it in my grandchildren’s school projects, where boys often dominate coding clubs without much encouragement, while girls hesitate to participate, fearing they won’t be taken seriously. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than awareness—it demands systemic change. Schools should integrate diverse role models into curricula, showing students that scientists and engineers come from all walks of life. Community programs, like those I’ve supported through gardening and rock climbing groups, can foster inclusivity by emphasizing teamwork and creativity over competition. The key is to create environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. It’s not about eliminating stereotypes but reframing them in ways that empower rather than discourage. In my own life, I’ve learned that curiosity and patience are the most powerful tools to dismantle barriers. By focusing on individual strengths and shared goals, we can build a future where STEM is accessible to all, regardless of who they are or where they come from.",
